many 1\n|-\n| '''France 2''' || align=center|2 & 1 || Sweden 2\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|2 || France 1 || align=center|halved || France 2\n|-\n| '''Sweden 2''' || align=center|3 & 2 || Germany 1\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|3 || '''Sweden 2''' || align=center|4 & 3 || France 1\n|-\n| '''France 2''' || align=center|1 up || Germany 1\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Seed !! Player !! W !! L !! H !! Points !! Finish\n|-\n| 12 || align=left|{{FRA}} 2 || 2 || 0 || 1 || 5 || 1\n|-\n| 13 || align=left|{{SWE}} 2 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 4 || 2\n|-\n| 4 || align=left|{{FRA}} 1 || 1 || 1 || 1 || 3 || 3\n|-\n| 5 || align=left|{{GER}} 1 || 0 || 3 || 0 || 0 || 4\n|}\n\n|}\n{| style=\"width: 60em\"\n|valign=top| \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Group C\n! Round !! Winner !! Score !! Loser\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|1 || '''Great Britain 3''' || align=center|5 & 4 || Iceland\n|-\n| '''Finland''' || align=center|3 & 2 || Austria\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|2 || Iceland || align=center|halved || Finland\n|-\n| '''Great Britain 3''' || align=center|5 & 3 || Austria\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|3 || Iceland || align=center|halved || Austria\n|-\n| Great Britain 3 || align=center|halved || Finland\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Seed !! Player !! W !! L !! H !! Points !! Finish\n|-\n| 6 || align=left|{{GBR2}} 3 || 2 || 0 || 1 || 5 || 1\n|-\n| 11 || align=left|{{FIN}} || 1 || 0 || 2 || 4 || 2\n|-\n| 3 || align=left|{{ISL}} || 0 || 1 || 2 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| 14 || align=left|{{AUT}} || 0 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 4\n|}\n \n|valign=top| \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Group D\n! Round !! Winner !! Score !! Loser\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|1 || '''Great Britain 2''' || align=center|3 & 2 || Sweden 1\n|-\n| '''Sweden 3''' || align=center|5 & 4 || Norway\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|2 || '''Great Britain 2''' || align=center|1 up|| Norway\n|-\n| '''Sweden 1''' || align=center|5 & 4 || Sweden 3\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2|3 || '''Sweden 3''' || align=center|2 up || Great Britain 2\n|-\n| '''Norway''' || align=center|2 & 1 || Sweden 1\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Seed !! Player !! W !! L !! H !! Points !! Finish\n|-\n| 15 || align=left|{{SWE}} 3 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 4 || 1\n|-\n| 2 || align=left|{{GBR2}} 2 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 4 || 2\n|-\n| 10 || align=left|{{NOR}} || 1 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| 7 || align=left|{{SWE}} 1 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 4\n|}\n\n|}\n\n====Medal bracket====\n''Sunday, 12 August''\n{{4TeamBracket-with 3rd\n| Team-Width = 130px\n| RD1        = Semifinals\n| RD2        = Gold medal match\n| RD3        = Bronze medal match\n\n| RD1-seed1  = 1\n| RD1-team1  = {{GBR2}} 1\n| RD1-score1 = \n| RD1-seed2  = 15\n| RD1-team2  = '''{{SWE}} 3'''\n| RD1-score2 = 1 up\n\n| RD1-seed3  = 12\n| RD1-team3  = '''{{FRA}} 2'''\n| RD1-score3 = {{nowrap| 5 & 4 }}\n| RD1-seed4  = 6\n| RD1-team4  = {{GBR2}} 3\n| RD1-score4 =\n\n| RD2-seed1  = 15\n| RD2-team1  = '''{{SWE}} 3'''\n| RD2-score1 = {{nowrap|20 holes}}\n| RD2-seed2  = 12\n| RD2-team2  = {{FRA}} 2\n| RD2-score2 =\n\n| RD3-seed1  = 1\n| RD3-team1  = {{GBR2}} 1\n| RD3-score1 = \n| RD3-seed2  = 6\n| RD3-team2  = '''{{GBR2}} 3'''\n| RD3-score2 = 3 & 1\n}}\n\n===Mixed team===\n\n{{Main|2018 European Golf Team Championships - Mixed team}}\n\nThe mixed team championship comprised eleven teams of four (2 men and 2 women) playing in 18-hole mixed foursomes stroke play on 11 August, with combined scores used for team's total score. Ties for medal positions were determined by a sudden-death playoff involving the low-scoring foursome from each team involved.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Place!!Nation!!Score!!To par\n|-\n| align=center|{{gold01}} || {{ISL}} || 70-71=141 || align=center|\u22123\n|-\n| align=center|{{silver02}} || {{GBR2}} 3 || 72-70=142 || align=center|\u22122\n|-\n| align=center|{{bronze03}} || {{SWE}} 2 || 70-73=143 || rowspan=2 align=center|\u22121\n|-\n| align=center|4 || {{ESP}} || 75-68=143\n|-\n| rowspan=2 align=center|T5 || {{GBR2}} 1 || 76-69=145 || rowspan=2 align=center|+1\n|-\n| {{SWE}} 1 || 72-73=145\n|-\n| align=center|7 || {{AUT}} || 75-72=147 || align=center|+3\n|-\n| align=center|8 || {{BEL}} || 77-71=148 || align=center|+4\n|-\n| rowspan=2 align=center|T9 || {{GBR2}} 2 || 76-73=149 || rowspan=2 align=center|+5\n|-\n| {{NOR}} || 73-76=149\n|-\n| align=center|11 || {{ITA}} || 76-74=150 || align=center|+6\n|}\nSweden 2 defeated Spain with a birdie at the first hole of the bronze medal playoff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2018/tournamentid=2018067/news/newsid=354758.html |title=Ice-cool Iceland win gold in mixed event |publisher=PGA European Tour |date=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Medalists==\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event|labelwidth=100|width=170}}\n|-\n|Men's team\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} '''Spain 1'''<br>[[Pedro Oriol]]<br>[[Scott Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n| {{flagicon|ISL}} '''Iceland'''<br>[[Birgir Haf\u00fe\u00f3rsson]]<br>[[Axel B\u00f3asson]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} '''Italy 2'''<br> [[Francesco Laporta]]<br>[[Alessandro Tadini]]\n|-\n|Women's team\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} '''Sweden 3'''<br>[[Cajsa Persson]]<br>[[Linda Wessberg]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} '''France 2'''<br>[[Justine Dreher]]<br>[[Manon Moll\u00e9]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} '''Great Britain 3'''<br>[[Meghan MacLaren]]<br>[[Michele Thomson]]\n|-\n| [[2018 European Golf Team Championships - Mixed team|Mixed team]]\n| {{flagicon|ISL}} '''Iceland'''<br />[[\u00d3laf\u00eda \u00de\u00f3runn Kristinsd\u00f3ttir]]<br />[[Birgir Haf\u00fe\u00f3rsson]]<br />[[Valdis Thora Jonsdottir]]<br />[[Axel B\u00f3asson]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} '''Great Britain 3'''<br />[[Meghan MacLaren]] <br /> [[Liam Johnston (golfer)|Liam Johnston]]<br />[[Michele Thomson]]<br />[[Connor Syme]]\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} '''Sweden 2'''<br />[[Daniel Jennevret]]<br />[[Oscar Flor\u00e9n]]<br />[[Johanna Gustavsson]]<br />[[Julia Engstr\u00f6m]]\n|}\n\n==Medal summary== \n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = GBR\n | flag_template  = \n | event          = \n | team           = \n | gold_ISL = 1 | silver_ISL = 1 | bronze_ISL = 0\n | gold_SWE = 1 | silver_SWE = 0 | bronze_SWE = 1\n | gold_ESP = 1 | silver_ESP = 0 | bronze_ESP = 0\n | gold_GBR = 0 | silver_GBR = 1 | bronze_GBR = 1 | host_GBR = yes\n | gold_FRA = 0 | silver_FRA = 1 | bronze_FRA = 0\n | gold_ITA = 0 | silver_ITA = 0 | bronze_ITA = 1\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{OfficialSite|https://www.europeanchampionships.com/sports/golf}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180730234601/https://www.glasgow2018.com/sports/golf European Championships Glasgow 2018 site]\n*[https://www.europeanchampionships.com/ECG2018/en/results-books/download/EC2018%20Golf%20Results%20Book.pdf Results book \u2212 Golf]\n*[http://www.europeantour.com/europeantour/season=2018/tournamentid=2018067/index.html Coverage on the European Tour site]\n*[https://ladieseuropeantour.com/tournament-page/?tourn=1810&season=2018 Coverage on the Ladies European Tour site]\n\n{{2018 European Championships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:European Golf Team Championships}}\n[[Category:2018 European Golf Team Championships| ]]\n[[Category:Team golf tournaments]]\n[[Category:Golf tournaments in Scotland|2018 European Golf Team Championships]]\n[[Category:Sport in Perth and Kinross]]\n[[Category:2018 European Championships|Golf]]\n[[Category:2018 in golf]]\n[[Category:2018 in Scottish sport]]\n[[Category:August 2018 sports events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_European_Golf_Team_Championships"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 1997", "text_new": "{{short description|1997 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title\t= MLS Cup 1997\n| image\t= MLS Cup 97 logo.gif\n| event\t= [[MLS Cup]]\n| team1\t= [[D.C. United]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2\t= [[Colorado Rapids]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = \n| date = October 26, 1997 \n| stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] \n| city = [[Washington, D.C.]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United) \n| referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n| attendance = 57,431 \n| weather = Rain, {{convert|46|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 1996|1996]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 1997''' was the second edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the post-season championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) in the United States. It was played on October 26, 1997, between [[D.C. United]] and the [[Colorado Rapids]] to determine the champion of the [[1997 Major League Soccer season|1997 season]]. The match was played in front of 57,431 spectators at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nD.C. United were defending champions and finished atop the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] and the [[Supporters' Shield|overall league standings]] despite being strained by runs in multiple competitions. Colorado had overhauled their roster after finishing last overall in the 1996 season and qualified for the playoffs with a [[Win\u2013loss record|losing record]], finishing fourth in the [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]], but earned two [[upset (sports)|upset]] victories in the playoffs. As finalists, D.C. United and the Colorado Rapids both earned berths to play in the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]].\n\nDuring a rainstorm that mirrored the [[MLS Cup 1996|previous final]], D.C. repeated as MLS Cup champions by winning 2\u20131. The hosts took a lead through [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] in the 37th minute and extended it with a header by [[Tony Sanneh]] in the 68th minute. Substitute [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] scored a consolation goal for Colorado in the 75th minute, but the team were unable to draw level despite several chances. The announced crowd of 57,431 was the second-largest attendance for a sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:RFK Stadium satellite view.png|thumb|left|Aerial view of [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the host venue of MLS Cup 1997]]\n\n[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the home of defending champions [[D.C. United]], was selected as the host of the second MLS Cup on December 17, 1996.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 18, 1996 |title=MLS likes weekend matches |page=D2 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref> The stadium was opened in 1961 and was primarily used for American football and baseball, but previously hosted the 1980 [[Soccer Bowl]] and the [[1996 U.S. Open Cup|1996 U.S. Open Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 31, 1996 |title=United Captures Another Title |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> It also hosted several matches during the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Olympics men's soccer tournament]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 20, 2017 |title=American soccer made its home at aging, funky RFK Stadium |page= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/19/soccer-at-rfk-stadium-its-dirty-and-disgusting-and-ugly-but-its-ours/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe league sold 32,000 tickets for the final in mid-October after D.C. United advanced to the [[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Finals|Conference Finals]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Stevens |date=October 15, 1997 |title=On Novel Field, D.C. Hopes To Say: Goodbye, Columbus |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> After the team clinched an appearance in the final, the remainder of the stadium's 56,000 seats were sold out and 1,000 [[bleacher]] seats were added.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 21, 1997 |title=D.C. Is United for MLS Title Game |page=E1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club [[Association football|soccer]] league based in the United States that began play in 1996. The league's [[1997 Major League Soccer season|second season]] was contested by ten teams organized into two conferences, each playing 32 matches during the regular season from April to September. Teams faced opponents from the same conference four times during the regular season and from outside their conference three or four times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=December 5, 1995 |title=Major League Soccer Sets Inaugural Schedule |page=C5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-12-05/sports/sp-10453_1_major-league-soccer |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> MLS continued to use the modified version of the sport's rules that it adopted for the 1996 season, including a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|penalty shootout]] from {{convert|35|yd|m}} to decide tied matches (for which the winners earned one point) and a [[countdown clock]] that stopped during [[Ball in and out of play|dead plays]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Macguire |first=Eoghan |date=March 6, 2015 |title=MLS at 20: Sunrise on football's final frontier? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/06/football/mls-20-sunrise-sunset/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Dure22\">{{cite book |last=Dure |first=Beau |year=2010 |title=Long-Range Goals: The Success Story of Major League Soccer |pages=22\u201324 |publisher=[[Potomac Books]] |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-59797-509-4 |oclc=500783910 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe top four teams from each conference qualified for the playoffs, which were organized into three rounds and played in October. The first two rounds, named the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals, were [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with a hosting advantage for the higher seed. The winners of the Conference Finals advanced to the single-match MLS Cup final, which would be held at a predetermined neutral venue.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was contested by defending champions and hosts D.C. United, who finished first in the regular season standings, and the [[Colorado Rapids]], who finished fourth in the Western Conference. The two finalists swept through the playoffs by winning the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals in two legs. During three regular season meetings between the two teams, D.C. won 5\u20132 in April and 5\u20130 in June, while Colorado won in a shootout following a 2\u20132 draw in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=October 26, 1997 |title=In Final, 'White Shoes' Rapids Hope To Remain On Yellow Brick Road |page=F2 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279201/in_final_white_shoes_rapids_hope_to/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Rapids reached the final through a \"[[Cinderella (sports)|Cinderella run]]\" in the playoffs and were considered [[underdog]]s to defending champions D.C. United.<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\"/>\n\n===D.C. United===\n{{see also|1997 D.C. United season}}\n\nInaugural season champions D.C. United retained most of their players and made few changes during the offseason, trading midfielder [[Shawn Medved]] to the [[San Jose Clash]] and acquiring defender [[Carlos Llamosa]] in the [[1997 MLS Supplemental Draft|supplemental draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=March 29, 1997 |title=United looks strong for defense of title |page=D4 |work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref> Nine of their starting players were called up at various times to their national teams for [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round|World Cup qualifying]], giving reserve players an opportunity to earn a starting spot.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 1997 |title=MLS teams have to cope with World Cup qualifying |page=C8 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"DC-Review\">{{cite web |title=History: 1997 season |url=https://www.dcunited.com/media-guide/history/1997 |publisher=D.C. United |accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> D.C. went on a preseason tour that included matches in Japan and Hong Kong, earning a 6\u20132 [[win\u2013loss record]], and returned to open the season against MLS Cup opponents [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] with a shootout win.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=March 29, 1997 |title=MLS opens second season with more refined outlook |page=C4 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40103290/mls_opens_second_season_with_more/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=March 30, 1997 |title=Galaxy Stumbles in Home Opener to D.C. United |page=C3 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40104351/galaxy_stumbles_in_home_opener_to_dc/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned one shootout win and three wins in regulation time to put them atop the Eastern Conference standings early in the season, highlighted by the performance of rookie goalkeeper [[Scott Garlick]], who replaced starter [[Mark Simpson (soccer)|Mark Simpson]] during his stint with an indoor team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=April 24, 1997 |title=Team collects outstanding keepers, and the strategy is paying off nicely |page=B6 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then drew four times and lost three of the shootouts,<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=May 19, 1997 |title=No Practice Is Perfect In Shootout Tiebreaker |page=D2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> briefly losing first place in the East in May before retaking it by the end of the month.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=May 23, 1997 |title=United dashes Clash, 3-1, to regain 1st place |page=D8 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154216/united_dashes_clash_31_to_regain_1st/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Despite losing Bolivian players [[Marco Etcheverry]] and [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] to the national team for six weeks, D.C. won their next five matches but lost 6\u20131 to the [[Kansas City Wizards]] on June 21, ending a 22-match unbeaten streak in regulation time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Satterly |first=Rich J. |date=June 22, 1997 |title=Wizards Make History Out of United, 6-1 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. United also had six players in the starting lineup for the [[1997 MLS All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], which was won 5\u20134 by the East.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=July 10, 1997 |title=East Bests West in a Goalfest; Valderrama Is MVP In 5-4 All-Star Win |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nAfter the All-Star Game in early July, D.C. United went through a series of underwhelming performances, including three regulation losses and one shootout loss in six matches, blamed in part on injuries to Etcheverry and captain [[John Harkes]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 4, 1997 |title=United's Recent Losses Are Missed Opportunities |page=D9 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Mitch |date=August 3, 1997 |title=Shootout loss to Rapids extends United's slump |page=C1 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then entered a stretch of 13 matches in 36 days, forced by their participation in the [[1997 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] (finishing third) and [[1997 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] (advancing to the semifinals). D.C. United went 8\u20134\u20131 in all competitions through the end of August, including three wins out of four matches in regular season play during a stretch of five matches in twelve days.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 28, 1997 |title=United Retaliates, Quells Revolution, 3-2 |page=C3 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team made further changes to their goalkeepers, as Simpson had undergone two knee surgeries and backup [[Jeff Causey]] was signed by the [[New England Revolution]]; in their place, Scott Garlick and rookie [[Tom Presthus]] were rotated between matches as starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 27, 1997 |title=United Hopes Goalkeepers Have Saved Their Best for Last |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On August 17, [[Mario Gori]] and [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]] were arrested for an alleged rape at a Columbus hotel, but released the following day on bail and allowed to continue playing for the team;<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=August 29, 1997 |title=United players' hearing continued |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=Athelia |date=September 6, 1997 |title=Ohio Grand Jury Indicts United's Diaz Arce, Gori |page=B1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/09/06/ohio-grand-jury-indicts-uniteds-diaz-arce-gori/75b6b9e1-f978-475b-8d67-3dfa660c5941/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> the case was later dropped without charges in January 1998 after the alleged victim declined to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=January 16, 1998 |title=United Charges Dismissed |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/01/16/united-charges-dismissed/d717876b-5f56-4b2a-b257-aad495ac4bff/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned their playoff berth with their first win against the Kansas City Wizards in franchise history after five earlier losses,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=September 1, 1997 |title=D.C. United finds way to upend Wizards, 2-0 |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154989/dc_united_finds_way_to_upend_wizards/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> and subsequently clinched first place in the Eastern Conference with a 3\u20132 shootout win against New England.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 17, 1997 |title=D.C. Clinches 1st Place In Eastern Conference |page=C5 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team continued to heavily rotate lineups and rested eight starting players in the second of a home-and-away series against the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]], winning 5\u20131 despite losing the first match with most of their regular starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Page |first=Rodney |date=September 27, 1997 |title=D.C. subs embarrass Mutiny |page=C9 |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40155123/dc_subs_embarrass_mutiny/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. finished the regular season atop the league-wide standings with 55 points and a 21\u201311 record, but fell short of matching the Mutiny's record 58 points from the 1996 season after losing to the MetroStars in their last match.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 29, 1997 |title=MetroStars 3, United 1: D.C. Loses in a Daze at RFK |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team showed its roster depth by using a different lineup for all 39 league and cup matches, including 24 different starting players.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 8, 1997 |title=Its Depth Charges D.C. United; Wegerle Will Start Over Diaz Arce |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Bruce Arena was named [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]], [[Eddie Pope]] was named [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|Defender of the Year]], and four United players were included in the [[MLS Best XI]].<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Bachelor |first=Blaine |date=October 26, 1997 |title=Underdog Rapids play for title |page=10 |work=[[The Tampa Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279070/underdog_rapids_play_for_title/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. faced New England in the Conference Semifinals and earned a 4\u20131 victory in the first leg of the series at home. [[Roy Wegerle]], a midseason signing from Colorado, scored to give United a halftime lead and added a second before Jaime Moreno scored two more; New England defender [[Mike Burns (soccer)|Mike Burns]] scored a consolation goal with a minute left in the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 6, 1997 |title=United Kicks Things Off Right, 4-1 |page=C1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/06/united-kicks-things-off-right-4-1/661cca9c-ae61-4fbc-b061-ffe3da34c3ec/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> In the away leg at [[Foxboro Stadium]], D.C. were held to a 1\u20131 draw in regulation time, with a goal for [[Richie Williams]] canceled out by [[Joe-Max Moore]]'s penalty kick in the 72nd minute. The two teams played in a seven-round shootout that ended 4\u20133 in United's favor after a series of saves from goalkeepers [[Walter Zenga]] and Tom Presthus that was broken up by defender Carlos Llamosa's conversion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 9, 1997 |title=D.C. United Eliminates Revolution in Shootout |page=B1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Finals, D.C. played the third-seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] after they had eliminated the Tampa Bay Mutiny. In the first leg, played without Etcheverry who was on national team duty, United took a three-goal halftime lead that was reduced by two for a 3\u20132 victory after a second half surge in pressure and chances from the Crew.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 13, 1997 |title=United Thrives in the 1st Half, Survives the Crew in 2nd, 3-2 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. clinched their second MLS Cup appearance with a 1\u20130 win at [[Ohio Stadium]] in Columbus, with D\u00edaz Arce scoring the lone goal in the 47th minute from within the {{convert|6|yd|m|adj=mid|spell=in}} box.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 16, 1997 |title=United Sweeps Crew, Advances to Title Game |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/16/united-sweeps-crew-advances-to-title-game/13ceff67-89db-4121-9d0e-f21106aae392/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Colorado Rapids===\n\nThe Colorado Rapids finished last overall in MLS during the league's inaugural season, with a 11\u201321 record under head coach [[Bob Houghton]], who was replaced in the offseason by [[Glenn Myernick]].<ref>{{cite news |last=French |first=Scott |date=October 25, 1997 |title=Rapids rapidly shed laughing stock role |page=B4 |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]}}</ref> Myernick and new general manager [[Dan Counce]] implemented a possession-oriented style and overhauled the Rapids roster by signing eleven new players, including trades to acquire defender [[Peter Vermes]] and midfielders [[Paul Bravo]] and [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]]. The team also signed goalkeeper [[Marcus Hahnemann]] and forward [[Wolde Harris]] from the second-division [[A-League (1995\u20132004)|A-League]] and were allocated Mexican midfielder [[David Pati\u00f1o]] by the league.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\">{{cite news |last=Landman |first=Brian |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Need for Rapid changes recognized, met in Denver |page=C7 |work=Tampa Bay Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004580/need_for_rapid_changes_recognized_met/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Mr. Fix-It When It Counce |page=17 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004749/mr_fixit_when_it_counce/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nAfter a short preseason tour in Mexico and Florida, the Rapids opened the season without forward [[Jean Harbor]] and several defenders who were either injured or called up to national team duty, winning only twice in their first seven matches.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 8, 1997 |title=Rapids shift camp to Florida |page=C16 |work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]}}</ref> The team were able to consistently earn wins through the summer, with a 9\u201310 record by mid-July that allowed them to reach second in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=July 20, 1997 |title=Rapids need to burn Dallas to say in hunt |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The Rapids finished fourth in the conference with a losing 14\u201318 record during the regular season, which ended with a six-match losing streak.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=October 17, 1997 |title=D.C. feels at home defending its title |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sulat |first=Nate |date=November 9, 2010 |title=History of conference championship upsets |url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/post/2010/11/09/history-conference-championship-upsets |publisher=[[Colorado Rapids]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> Leading goalscorers Bravo and [[Chris Henderson]], along with defender [[Marcelo Balboa]], were credited with the team's improved regular season performance.<ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 24, 1997 |title=Rapids make rapid rise to title game |page=15 |work=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40005459/rapids_make_rapid_rise_to_title_game/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Colorado played against the conference-leading Kansas City Wizards, who had defeated the Rapids in all four of their regular season fixtures.<ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 4, 1997 |title=Wizards hope to ride Rapids again in series |page=D1 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]]}}</ref> The first leg at Kansas City's [[Arrowhead Stadium]] finished in a 3\u20130 [[upset (sports)|upset]] victory for the Rapids, despite missing Paz and Balboa. The victory was credited to a disciplined performance by the Rapids defense, several saves from goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann, and attackers who took advantage of mistakes from the Wizards.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids' disciplined game stuns Kansas City in playoff opener |page=C5 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids stun Wizards |page=C15 |work=The Kansas City Star}}</ref> The Rapids began the second leg at home by conceding a goal to Wizards forward [[Vitalis Takawira]], but equalized within minutes and took a lead after halftime with goals from Paul Bravo. The match ended in a 3\u20132 win for Colorado, who swept the playoffs series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 9, 1997 |title=Rapids see Wizards off and out of the playoffs |page=C16 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref>\n\nThe Rapids advanced to play in the Conference Final against the [[Dallas Burn]], who had defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy in another upset from the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 12, 1997 |title=Surprising Rapids aim to cool off Burn in conference finals |page=C9 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Colorado won 1\u20130 in the first leg, played in Dallas, with a [[Header (association football)|header]] in the 42nd minute from defender [[Sean Henderson]]; the Burn had several chances to equalize, including a [[Free kick (association football)|free kick]] in the final five seconds that hit the [[Goalpost|post]], but were unable to capitalize.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dorson |first=Jill R. |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Last-second effort not enough for Burn |page=1 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Rapids win on Henderson's goal |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> In the second leg, played at [[Mile High Stadium]] in Denver, Dallas took an early lead in the fifth minute but were set back by an equalizer from David Pati\u00f1o in the 23rd minute. The match remained tied until a scissored [[Volley (association football)|volley]] from Chris Henderson in the 87th minute clinched a 2\u20131 victory to win the conference championship for Colorado.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 16, 1997 |title=Rapids stay on right foot with 2-1 win |page=C1 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The team became the first to take a pair of brothers, Chris and Sean Henderson, to the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=November 19, 2016 |title=Top 5 MLS Conference Championship moments |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/11/19/top-5-mls-conference-championship-moments |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away). Playoffs were in [[best of three|best-of-three]] format.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|[[D.C. United]]\n!Round\n!colspan=2|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|-\n|colspan=2 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[D.C. United]]'''||'''32'''||'''17'''||'''4'''||'''11'''||'''55'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Tampa Bay Mutiny]]||32||14||3||15||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Columbus Crew]]||32||12||3||17||'''39'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|4||align=left|[[New England Revolution]]||32||11||4||17||'''37'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|NY/NJ MetroStars]]||32||11||2||19||'''35'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[1997 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=2 valign=top|4th place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|1||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||32||14||7||11||'''49'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||32||14||2||16||'''44'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||32||13||3||16||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''4'''||align=left|'''[[Colorado Rapids]]'''||'''32'''||'''12'''||'''2'''||'''18'''||'''38'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[San Jose Clash]]||32||9||3||20||'''30'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|[[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[New England Revolution]] (2\u20130)}}\n|4\u20131 (H), 1\u20131 {{nowrap|(4\u20133 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|SO]])}} (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Kansas City Wizards]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20130 (A), 3\u20132 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Columbus Crew]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20132 (H), 1\u20130 (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Dallas Burn]] (2\u20130)}}\n|1\u20130 (A), 2\u20131 (H)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe match was broadcast on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in the United States, where it was watched by an estimated television audience of 2.2&nbsp;million viewers, setting a record that would stand until the [[MLS Cup 2016|2016 final]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 13, 2016 |title=Sounders score big on TV in MLS Cup final |url=https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/sports/mls/sounders/2016/12/13/sounders-score-big-tv-mls-cup-final/95409760/ |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Phil Schoen]] and [[Ty Keough]] reprised their roles from the previous final as play-by-play and [[color commentator]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=October 17, 1997 |title=MLS announces six-year TV deal with ABC, ESPN |page=C24 |work=USA Today}}</ref> The match was also televised in more than 100 foreign markets by [[ESPN International]].<ref name=\"Post-Dream\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 26, 1997 |title=MLS, United on Verge Of Realizing a Dream |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:Moreno-toronto-rfk.jpg|thumb|right|D.C. forward [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] scored the opening goal and was named the match's [[most valuable player]].]]\n\nThe MLS Cup final kicked off at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. with an announced [[sellout]] crowd of 57,431 spectators at RFK Memorial Stadium, setting a new attendance record for a single playoff match.<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\">{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reigns and MLS shines despite rain |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40245859/united_reigns_and_mls_shines_despite/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The match was played during a rainstorm in cold conditions, which mirrored the weather during the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural final]] and deterred some ticket-holding fans from attending.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\">{{cite news |last=Gildea |first=William |date=October 27, 1997 |title=A Great Day for Playing in the Rain |page=A1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/scene27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reaches MLS goal again |page=D2 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48895364/united-reaches-mls-goal-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. controlled the opening minutes, taking their first shot within 25 seconds, but Colorado used counterattacks to find chances and force goalkeeper Scott Garlick to make three saves and a foul that earned him a [[yellow card]].<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Garlick Saves Best in Last Game |page=D10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mlside27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The hosts responded with their own counterattacking plays that were channeled by [[Tony Sanneh]] towards Jaime Moreno, who could not finish his first few chances.<ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United Defeats Rapids, 2-1, Wins Second Title |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mls27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\">{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=October 26, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #25 Blonde Bombshell |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/27/top-50-mls-cup-moments-25-blonde-bombshell |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. took a 1\u20130 lead in the 37th minute after a cross from Sanneh to Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce, who [[dummy (football)|dummied]] the ball at the top of the [[penalty area]]. The cross fell to Moreno, who took a shot from {{convert|12|yd|m}} that rolled past Marcus Hahnemann and two Colorado defenders.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\"/> The Rapids were outshot 8\u20135 in the first half, with only one shot in the final 24 minutes.<ref name=\"Rocky\">{{cite news |last=Lindsay |first=John |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United way isn't generous to Rapids |page=C4 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> They attempted to find an equalizer early in the second half and had two chances through David Pati\u00f1o that were not finished after missing a through ball and later hitting teammate [[Steve Rammel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Gary |date=October 26, 1997 |title=D.C. United, again |page=S12 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=\"SS-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=October 22, 1997 |title=United they stand |pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ C9], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894996/united-they-stand-p-c14/ C14] |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nSanneh extended the lead for D.C. in the 68th minute, scoring with a header at the far post on a high cross from John Harkes after cleaning up a cleared corner kick. The team continued its attacking pressure, but shifted to a defensive style to prepare for counterattacks from the Rapids.<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Marcelo Balboa moved up into the midfield and attempted a [[bicycle kick]] in the 70th minute that was saved by Garlick.<ref>{{cite news |last=Firchau |first=Nick |date=October 23, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #28 Biker Boss |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/24/top-50-mls-cup-moments-28-biker-boss |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Colorado scored a consolation goal in the 75th minute from substitute Adri\u00e1n Paz, who struck the ball from a tight angle in the penalty area on an assist from Pati\u00f1o.<ref name=\"SS-Recap\"/> A chance to equalize came less than a minute later as Rapids forward Wolde Harris took an unimpeded shot from {{convert|20|yd|m}} that flew over the crossbar.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"NYT-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United Takes Lead, Then Holds On to Retain Its Title |page=C3 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/27/sports/soccer-united-takes-lead-then-holds-on-to-retain-its-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> D.C. responded with their own attacks that were shut down by the Rapids, including two fouls that were described as potential [[penalty kick]]s that went uncalled by referee [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]].<ref name=\"Globe-Recap\"/> The hosts won 2\u20131 to claim their second MLS Cup title;<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Moreno was named the MLS Cup [[most valuable player]] for his performance, which included setting up plays throughout the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tucker |first=Bryan |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Moreno Makes Most of Opportunity |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/bryan27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news |last=Jensen |first=Mike |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United again reigns in the rain |page=D3 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394764/dc_united_again_reigns_in_the_rain/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date = October 26, 1997\n|time = 3:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[D.C. United]]\n|score = 2\u20131\n|report= [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/1997 Report]\n|team2 = [[Colorado Rapids]]\n|goals1 = \n*[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Moreno]] {{goal|37}}\n*[[Tony Sanneh|Sanneh]] {{goal|68}}\n|goals2 = [[Adri\u00e1n Paz|Paz]] {{goal|75}}\n|stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]]\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|attendance = 57,431\n|referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:92%;\"\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _thinredborder\n |pattern_b  = _DCU_96h\n |pattern_ra = _thinredborder\n |pattern_sh = _DCU_96\n |pattern_so = _3_stripes_white\n |leftarm    = 000000\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = 000000\n |shorts     = 000000\n |socks      = 000000\n |title      = D.C. United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = \n |pattern_b  = \n |pattern_ra = \n |pattern_sh = \n |pattern_so = \n |leftarm    = FFFFFF\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = FFFFFF\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = FFFFFF\n |title      = Colorado Rapids\n}}\n|}\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Garlick]] || {{yel|20}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18''' ||{{flagicon|COL}} [[Carlos Llamosa]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Pope]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''24''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[David Vaudreuil]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10''' ||{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Marco Etcheverry]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[John Harkes]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''20''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Sanneh]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''16''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richie Williams]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{in5}}''None used''\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Head coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bruce Arena]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcus Hahnemann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''12''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Kmosko]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Martinez (soccer)|Chris Martinez]] || || {{suboff|59}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Trittschuh]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vermes]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcelo Balboa]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|86}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Bravo]] || || {{suboff|27}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Henderson]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sean Henderson]] || || {{suboff|81}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[David Pati\u00f1o]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Rammel]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Wolde Harris]] || || {{subon|27}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|URU}} [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] || || {{subon|59}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ross Paule]] || || {{subon|81}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Head coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Glenn Myernick]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Steve Olson\n<br />Greg Barkey\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time with a [[countdown clock]]\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|Penalty shootout]] from 35 yards if scores still tied.\n*Maximum of three substitutions.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was the first sports championship for the Washington, D.C. area to be won at a stadium in the city.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 8, 2007 |title=D.C. United announce ticket prices for 2008 season |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/23/dc-united-announce-ticket-prices-2008-season |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> The announced attendance of 57,431 came within 600 spectators of breaking the overall record for largest sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium, held by the United States\u2013Portugal match during the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"Post-Dream\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 26, 1997 |title=United 2, Rapids 1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/united27.htm |work=The Washington Post |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> It was the first day in which there were large sporting events at both of the major outdoor stadiums in the D.C. area, as [[Jack Kent Cooke Stadium]] also hosted an [[NFL]] game.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\"/> A railing in the upper stands at RFK Memorial Stadium collapsed during the celebrations after the match, causing minor injuries to 50 fans.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Dozens injured when railings collapse at RFK after MLS Cup |page=8 |work=[[The Independent-Record]] |location=Helena, Montana |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394737/mls_cup_1997_recap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nThree days after the MLS Cup final, D.C. United played the Dallas Burn in the [[1997 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup Final]] with a chance to earn the league's first \"[[Treble (association football)|treble]]\". The Burn and United played to a scoreless draw and D.C. lost 5\u20133 in the ensuing penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=November 27, 2017 |title=Could Toronto FC become the first MLS team to win a domestic treble? |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/11/27/could-toronto-fc-become-first-mls-team-win-domestic-treble |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The team, with the exception of Etcheverry and Moreno, was honored with a reception at the [[White House]] by President [[Bill Clinton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Liz |date=April 7, 1998 |title=Two-Time Champion United Honored at White House |page=E6 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/04/07/two-time-champion-united-honored-at-white-house/4a2da7f9-c817-4ccf-a00a-afe3d4cad126/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> D.C. returned to the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]], where they lost to the [[Chicago Fire SC|Chicago Fire]], and in [[MLS Cup 1999|1999]], where they defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy. <ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 22, 1999 |title=D.C.'s Two First-Half Goals Doom Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1999/mlscup/united22.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. and Colorado qualified as the U.S. representatives for the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], which was hosted at RFK Memorial Stadium in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=April 26, 1998 |title=On Second Thought, United Seeks Change |page=D6 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The Rapids were eliminated in the qualifying playoff round, played in a home-and-away series against [[Club Le\u00f3n]] of Mexico, by a 4\u20133 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 16, 1998 |title=Leon preys on, eliminates shorthanded Rapids 4\u20132 |page=C13 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> D.C. entered the competition in the quarterfinals and eliminated Trinidadian club [[Joe Public F.C.|Joe Public]], Le\u00f3n, and Mexican champion [[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|Toluca]] on their way to winning the Champions' Cup, becoming the first American team to be crowned as continental champions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 17, 1998 |title=United Steps Up, Wins Champions' Cup |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 16, 1998 |title=United Faces Toluca Seeking Title, Respect |page=D6 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> United then advanced to the [[1998 Copa Interamericana]], where they defeated South American champions [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]] of Brazil over two legs played in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=December 6, 1998 |title=D.C. stops Brazilians |page=C17 |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18125728/interamerican_cup_recap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{1997 in American soccer}}\n{{D.C. United matches}}\n{{Colorado Rapids}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1997 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:1997 Major League Soccer season|*Cup]]\n[[Category:D.C. United matches|MLS Cup 97]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rapids matches|MLS Cup 97]]\n[[Category:Soccer in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:October 1997 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1997 in sports in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title\t= MLS Cup 1997\n| image\t= MLS Cup 97 logo.gif\n| event\t= [[MLS Cup]]\n| team1\t= [[D.C. United]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2\t= [[Colorado Rapids]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = \n| date = October 26, 1997 \n| stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] \n| city = [[Washington, D.C.]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United) \n| referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n| attendance = 57,431 \n| weather = Rain, {{convert|46|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 1996|1996]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 1997''' was the second edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the post-season championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) in the United States. It was played on October 26, 1997, between [[D.C. United]] and the [[Colorado Rapids]] to determine the champion of the [[1997 Major League Soccer season|1997 season]]. The match was played in front of 57,431 spectators at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nD.C. United were defending champions and finished atop the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] and the [[Supporters' Shield|overall league standings]] despite being strained by runs in multiple competitions. Colorado had overhauled their roster after finishing last overall in the 1996 season and qualified for the playoffs with a [[Win\u2013loss record|losing record]], finishing fourth in the [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]], but earned two [[upset (sports)|upset]] victories in the playoffs. As finalists, D.C. United and the Colorado Rapids both earned berths to play in the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]].\n\nDuring a rainstorm that mirrored the [[MLS Cup 1996|previous final]], D.C. repeated as MLS Cup champions by winning 2\u20131. The hosts took a lead through [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] in the 37th minute and extended it with a header by [[Tony Sanneh]] in the 68th minute. Substitute [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] scored a consolation goal for Colorado in the 75th minute, but the team were unable to draw level despite several chances. The announced crowd of 57,431 was the second-largest attendance for a sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:RFK Stadium satellite view.png|thumb|left|Aerial view of [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the host venue of MLS Cup 1997]]\n\n[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the home of defending champions [[D.C. United]], was selected as the host of the second MLS Cup on December 17, 1996.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 18, 1996 |title=MLS likes weekend matches |page=D2 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref> The stadium was opened in 1961 and was primarily used for American football and baseball, but previously hosted the 1980 [[Soccer Bowl]] and the [[1996 U.S. Open Cup|1996 U.S. Open Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 31, 1996 |title=United Captures Another Title |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> It also hosted several matches during the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Olympics men's soccer tournament]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 20, 2017 |title=American soccer made its home at aging, funky RFK Stadium |page= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/19/soccer-at-rfk-stadium-its-dirty-and-disgusting-and-ugly-but-its-ours/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe league sold 32,000 tickets for the final in mid-October after D.C. United advanced to the [[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Finals|Conference Finals]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Stevens |date=October 15, 1997 |title=On Novel Field, D.C. Hopes To Say: Goodbye, Columbus |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> After the team clinched an appearance in the final, the remainder of the stadium's 56,000 seats were sold out and 1,000 [[bleacher]] seats were added.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 21, 1997 |title=D.C. Is United for MLS Title Game |page=E1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club [[Association football|soccer]] league based in the United States that began play in 1996. The league's [[1997 Major League Soccer season|second season]] was contested by ten teams organized into two conferences, each playing 32 matches during the regular season from April to September. Teams faced opponents from the same conference four times during the regular season and from outside their conference three or four times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=December 5, 1995 |title=Major League Soccer Sets Inaugural Schedule |page=C5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-12-05/sports/sp-10453_1_major-league-soccer |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> MLS continued to use the modified version of the sport's rules that it adopted for the 1996 season, including a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|penalty shootout]] from {{convert|35|yd|m}} to decide tied matches (for which the winners earned one point) and a [[countdown clock]] that stopped during [[Ball in and out of play|dead plays]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Macguire |first=Eoghan |date=March 6, 2015 |title=MLS at 20: Sunrise on football's final frontier? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/06/football/mls-20-sunrise-sunset/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Dure22\">{{cite book |last=Dure |first=Beau |year=2010 |title=Long-Range Goals: The Success Story of Major League Soccer |pages=22\u201324 |publisher=[[Potomac Books]] |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-59797-509-4 |oclc=500783910 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe top four teams from each conference qualified for the playoffs, which were organized into three rounds and played in October. The first two rounds, named the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals, were [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with a hosting advantage for the higher seed. The winners of the Conference Finals advanced to the single-match MLS Cup final, which would be held at a predetermined neutral venue.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was contested by defending champions and hosts D.C. United, who finished first in the regular season standings, and the [[Colorado Rapids]], who finished fourth in the Western Conference. The two finalists swept through the playoffs by winning the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals in two legs. During three regular season meetings between the two teams, D.C. won 5\u20132 in April and 5\u20130 in June, while Colorado won in a shootout following a 2\u20132 draw in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=October 26, 1997 |title=In Final, 'White Shoes' Rapids Hope To Remain On Yellow Brick Road |page=F2 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279201/in_final_white_shoes_rapids_hope_to/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Rapids reached the final through a \"[[Cinderella (sports)|Cinderella run]]\" in the playoffs and were considered [[underdog]]s to defending champions D.C. United.<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\"/>\n\n===D.C. United===\n{{see also|1997 D.C. United season}}\n\nInaugural season champions D.C. United retained most of their players and made few changes during the offseason, trading midfielder [[Shawn Medved]] to the [[San Jose Clash]] and acquiring defender [[Carlos Llamosa]] in the [[1997 MLS Supplemental Draft|supplemental draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=March 29, 1997 |title=United looks strong for defense of title |page=D4 |work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref> Nine of their starting players were called up at various times to their national teams for [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round|World Cup qualifying]], giving reserve players an opportunity to earn a starting spot.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 1997 |title=MLS teams have to cope with World Cup qualifying |page=C8 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"DC-Review\">{{cite web |title=History: 1997 season |url=https://www.dcunited.com/media-guide/history/1997 |publisher=D.C. United |accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> D.C. went on a preseason tour that included matches in Japan and Hong Kong, earning a 6\u20132 [[win\u2013loss record]], and returned to open the season against MLS Cup opponents [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] with a shootout win.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=March 29, 1997 |title=MLS opens second season with more refined outlook |page=C4 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40103290/mls_opens_second_season_with_more/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=March 30, 1997 |title=Galaxy Stumbles in Home Opener to D.C. United |page=C3 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40104351/galaxy_stumbles_in_home_opener_to_dc/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned one shootout win and three wins in regulation time to put them atop the Eastern Conference standings early in the season, highlighted by the performance of rookie goalkeeper [[Scott Garlick]], who replaced starter [[Mark Simpson (soccer)|Mark Simpson]] during his stint with an indoor team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=April 24, 1997 |title=Team collects outstanding keepers, and the strategy is paying off nicely |page=B6 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then drew four times and lost three of the shootouts,<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=May 19, 1997 |title=No Practice Is Perfect In Shootout Tiebreaker |page=D2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> briefly losing first place in the East in May before retaking it by the end of the month.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=May 23, 1997 |title=United dashes Clash, 3-1, to regain 1st place |page=D8 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154216/united_dashes_clash_31_to_regain_1st/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Despite losing Bolivian players [[Marco Etcheverry]] and [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] to the national team for six weeks, D.C. won their next five matches but lost 6\u20131 to the [[Kansas City Wizards]] on June 21, ending a 22-match unbeaten streak in regulation time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Satterly |first=Rich J. |date=June 22, 1997 |title=Wizards Make History Out of United, 6-1 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. United also had six players in the starting lineup for the [[1997 MLS All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], which was won 5\u20134 by the East.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=July 10, 1997 |title=East Bests West in a Goalfest; Valderrama Is MVP In 5-4 All-Star Win |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nAfter the All-Star Game in early July, D.C. United went through a series of underwhelming performances, including three regulation losses and one shootout loss in six matches, blamed in part on injuries to Etcheverry and captain [[John Harkes]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 4, 1997 |title=United's Recent Losses Are Missed Opportunities |page=D9 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Mitch |date=August 3, 1997 |title=Shootout loss to Rapids extends United's slump |page=C1 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then entered a stretch of 13 matches in 36 days, forced by their participation in the [[1997 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] (finishing third) and [[1997 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] (advancing to the semifinals). D.C. United went 8\u20134\u20131 in all competitions through the end of August, including three wins out of four matches in regular season play during a stretch of five matches in twelve days.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 28, 1997 |title=United Retaliates, Quells Revolution, 3-2 |page=C3 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team made further changes to their goalkeepers, as Simpson had undergone two knee surgeries and backup [[Jeff Causey]] was signed by the [[New England Revolution]]; in their place, Scott Garlick and rookie [[Tom Presthus]] were rotated between matches as starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 27, 1997 |title=United Hopes Goalkeepers Have Saved Their Best for Last |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On August 17, [[Mario Gori]] and [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]] were arrested for an alleged rape at a Columbus hotel, but released the following day on bail and allowed to continue playing for the team;<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=August 29, 1997 |title=United players' hearing continued |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=Athelia |date=September 6, 1997 |title=Ohio Grand Jury Indicts United's Diaz Arce, Gori |page=B1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/09/06/ohio-grand-jury-indicts-uniteds-diaz-arce-gori/75b6b9e1-f978-475b-8d67-3dfa660c5941/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> the case was later dropped without charges in January 1998 after the alleged victim declined to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=January 16, 1998 |title=United Charges Dismissed |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/01/16/united-charges-dismissed/d717876b-5f56-4b2a-b257-aad495ac4bff/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned their playoff berth with their first win against the Kansas City Wizards in franchise history after five earlier losses,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=September 1, 1997 |title=D.C. United finds way to upend Wizards, 2-0 |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154989/dc_united_finds_way_to_upend_wizards/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> and subsequently clinched first place in the Eastern Conference with a 3\u20132 shootout win against New England.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 17, 1997 |title=D.C. Clinches 1st Place In Eastern Conference |page=C5 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team continued to heavily rotate lineups and rested eight starting players in the second of a home-and-away series against the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]], winning 5\u20131 despite losing the first match with most of their regular starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Page |first=Rodney |date=September 27, 1997 |title=D.C. subs embarrass Mutiny |page=C9 |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40155123/dc_subs_embarrass_mutiny/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. finished the regular season atop the league-wide standings with 55 points and a 21\u201311 record, but fell short of matching the Mutiny's record 58 points from the 1996 season after losing to the MetroStars in their last match.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 29, 1997 |title=MetroStars 3, United 1: D.C. Loses in a Daze at RFK |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team showed its roster depth by using a different lineup for all 39 league and cup matches, including 24 different starting players.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 8, 1997 |title=Its Depth Charges D.C. United; Wegerle Will Start Over Diaz Arce |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Bruce Arena was named [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]], [[Eddie Pope]] was named [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|Defender of the Year]], and four United players were included in the [[MLS Best XI]].<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Bachelor |first=Blaine |date=October 26, 1997 |title=Underdog Rapids play for title |page=10 |work=[[The Tampa Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279070/underdog_rapids_play_for_title/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. faced New England in the Conference Semifinals and earned a 4\u20131 victory in the first leg of the series at home. [[Roy Wegerle]], a midseason signing from Colorado, scored to give United a halftime lead and added a second before Jaime Moreno scored two more; New England defender [[Mike Burns (soccer)|Mike Burns]] scored a consolation goal with a minute left in the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 6, 1997 |title=United Kicks Things Off Right, 4-1 |page=C1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/06/united-kicks-things-off-right-4-1/661cca9c-ae61-4fbc-b061-ffe3da34c3ec/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> In the away leg at [[Foxboro Stadium]], D.C. were held to a 1\u20131 draw in regulation time, with a goal for [[Richie Williams]] canceled out by [[Joe-Max Moore]]'s penalty kick in the 72nd minute. The two teams played in a seven-round shootout that ended 4\u20133 in United's favor after a series of saves from goalkeepers [[Walter Zenga]] and Tom Presthus that was broken up by defender Carlos Llamosa's conversion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 9, 1997 |title=D.C. United Eliminates Revolution in Shootout |page=B1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Finals, D.C. played the third-seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] after they had eliminated the Tampa Bay Mutiny. In the first leg, played without Etcheverry who was on national team duty, United took a three-goal halftime lead that was reduced by two for a 3\u20132 victory after a second half surge in pressure and chances from the Crew.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 13, 1997 |title=United Thrives in the 1st Half, Survives the Crew in 2nd, 3-2 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. clinched their second MLS Cup appearance with a 1\u20130 win at [[Ohio Stadium]] in Columbus, with D\u00edaz Arce scoring the lone goal in the 47th minute from within the {{convert|6|yd|m|adj=mid|spell=in}} box.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 16, 1997 |title=United Sweeps Crew, Advances to Title Game |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/16/united-sweeps-crew-advances-to-title-game/13ceff67-89db-4121-9d0e-f21106aae392/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Colorado Rapids===\n\nThe Colorado Rapids finished last overall in MLS during the league's inaugural season, with a 11\u201321 record under head coach [[Bob Houghton]], who was replaced in the offseason by [[Glenn Myernick]].<ref>{{cite news |last=French |first=Scott |date=October 25, 1997 |title=Rapids rapidly shed laughing stock role |page=B4 |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]}}</ref> Myernick and new general manager [[Dan Counce]] implemented a possession-oriented style and overhauled the Rapids roster by signing eleven new players, including trades to acquire defender [[Peter Vermes]] and midfielders [[Paul Bravo]] and [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]]. The team also signed goalkeeper [[Marcus Hahnemann]] and forward [[Wolde Harris]] from the second-division [[A-League (1995\u20132004)|A-League]] and were allocated Mexican midfielder [[David Pati\u00f1o]] by the league.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\">{{cite news |last=Landman |first=Brian |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Need for Rapid changes recognized, met in Denver |page=C7 |work=Tampa Bay Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004580/need_for_rapid_changes_recognized_met/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Mr. Fix-It When It Counce |page=17 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004749/mr_fixit_when_it_counce/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nAfter a short preseason tour in Mexico and Florida, the Rapids opened the season without forward [[Jean Harbor]] and several defenders who were either injured or called up to national team duty, winning only twice in their first seven matches.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 8, 1997 |title=Rapids shift camp to Florida |page=C16 |work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]}}</ref> The team were able to consistently earn wins through the summer, with a 9\u201310 record by mid-July that allowed them to reach second in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=July 20, 1997 |title=Rapids need to burn Dallas to say in hunt |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The Rapids finished fourth in the conference with a losing 14\u201318 record during the regular season, which ended with a six-match losing streak.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=October 17, 1997 |title=D.C. feels at home defending its title |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sulat |first=Nate |date=November 9, 2010 |title=History of conference championship upsets |url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/post/2010/11/09/history-conference-championship-upsets |publisher=[[Colorado Rapids]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> Leading goalscorers Bravo and [[Chris Henderson]], along with defender [[Marcelo Balboa]], were credited with the team's improved regular season performance.<ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 24, 1997 |title=Rapids make rapid rise to title game |page=15 |work=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40005459/rapids_make_rapid_rise_to_title_game/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Colorado played against the conference-leading Kansas City Wizards, who had defeated the Rapids in all four of their regular season fixtures.<ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 4, 1997 |title=Wizards hope to ride Rapids again in series |page=D1 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]]}}</ref> The first leg at Kansas City's [[Arrowhead Stadium]] finished in a 3\u20130 [[upset (sports)|upset]] victory for the Rapids, despite missing Paz and Balboa. The victory was credited to a disciplined performance by the Rapids defense, several saves from goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann, and attackers who took advantage of mistakes from the Wizards.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids' disciplined game stuns Kansas City in playoff opener |page=C5 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids stun Wizards |page=C15 |work=The Kansas City Star}}</ref> The Rapids began the second leg at home by conceding a goal to Wizards forward [[Vitalis Takawira]], but equalized within minutes and took a lead after halftime with goals from Paul Bravo. The match ended in a 3\u20132 win for Colorado, who swept the playoffs series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 9, 1997 |title=Rapids see Wizards off and out of the playoffs |page=C16 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref>\n\nThe Rapids advanced to play in the Conference Final against the [[Dallas Burn]], who had defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy in another upset from the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 12, 1997 |title=Surprising Rapids aim to cool off Burn in conference finals |page=C9 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Colorado won 1\u20130 in the first leg, played in Dallas, with a [[Header (association football)|header]] in the 42nd minute from defender [[Sean Henderson]]; the Burn had several chances to equalize, including a [[Free kick (association football)|free kick]] in the final five seconds that hit the [[Goalpost|post]], but were unable to capitalize.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dorson |first=Jill R. |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Last-second effort not enough for Burn |page=1 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Rapids win on Henderson's goal |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> In the second leg, played at [[Mile High Stadium]] in Denver, Dallas took an early lead in the fifth minute but were set back by an equalizer from David Pati\u00f1o in the 23rd minute. The match remained tied until a scissored [[Volley (association football)|volley]] from Chris Henderson in the 87th minute clinched a 2\u20131 victory to win the conference championship for Colorado.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 16, 1997 |title=Rapids stay on right foot with 2-1 win |page=C1 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The team became the first to take a pair of brothers, Chris and Sean Henderson, to the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=November 19, 2016 |title=Top 5 MLS Conference Championship moments |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/11/19/top-5-mls-conference-championship-moments |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away). Playoffs were in [[best of three|best-of-three]] format.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|[[D.C. United]]\n!Round\n!colspan=2|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|-\n|colspan=2 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[D.C. United]]'''||'''32'''||'''17'''||'''4'''||'''11'''||'''55'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Tampa Bay Mutiny]]||32||14||3||15||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Columbus Crew]]||32||12||3||17||'''39'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|4||align=left|[[New England Revolution]]||32||11||4||17||'''37'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|NY/NJ MetroStars]]||32||11||2||19||'''35'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[1997 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=2 valign=top|4th place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|1||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||32||14||7||11||'''49'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||32||14||2||16||'''44'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||32||13||3||16||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''4'''||align=left|'''[[Colorado Rapids]]'''||'''32'''||'''12'''||'''2'''||'''18'''||'''38'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[San Jose Clash]]||32||9||3||20||'''30'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|[[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[New England Revolution]] (2\u20130)}}\n|4\u20131 (H), 1\u20131 {{nowrap|(4\u20133 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|SO]])}} (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Kansas City Wizards]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20130 (A), 3\u20132 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Columbus Crew]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20132 (H), 1\u20130 (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Dallas Burn]] (2\u20130)}}\n|1\u20130 (A), 2\u20131 (H)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe match was broadcast on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in the United States, where it was watched by an estimated television audience of 2.2&nbsp;million viewers, setting a record that would stand until the [[MLS Cup 2016|2016 final]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 13, 2016 |title=Sounders score big on TV in MLS Cup final |url=https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/sports/mls/sounders/2016/12/13/sounders-score-big-tv-mls-cup-final/95409760/ |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Phil Schoen]] and [[Ty Keough]] reprised their roles from the previous final as play-by-play and [[color commentator]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=October 17, 1997 |title=MLS announces six-year TV deal with ABC, ESPN |page=C24 |work=USA Today}}</ref> The match was also televised in more than 100 foreign markets by [[ESPN International]].<ref name=\"Post-Dream\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 26, 1997 |title=MLS, United on Verge Of Realizing a Dream |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:Moreno-toronto-rfk.jpg|thumb|right|D.C. forward [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] scored the opening goal and was named the match's [[most valuable player]].]]\n\nThe MLS Cup final kicked off at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. with an announced attendance of 57,431 spectators at RFK Memorial Stadium, setting a new record for the league's post-season.<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\">{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reigns and MLS shines despite rain |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40245859/united_reigns_and_mls_shines_despite/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The match was played during a rainstorm in cold conditions, mirroring the weather during the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural final]] and deterring some ticket-holding fans from attending.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\">{{cite news |last=Gildea |first=William |date=October 27, 1997 |title=A Great Day for Playing in the Rain |page=A1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/scene27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reaches MLS goal again |page=D2 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48895364/united-reaches-mls-goal-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. controlled the opening minutes, taking their first shot within 25 seconds, but Colorado used counterattacks to find chances and force goalkeeper [[Scott Garlick]] to make three saves and a foul that earned him a yellow card.<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Garlick Saves Best in Last Game |page=D10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mlside27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The hosts responded with their own counterattacking plays that were channeled by [[Tony Sanneh]] towards Jaime Moreno, who could not finish his first few chances.<ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United Defeats Rapids, 2-1, Wins Second Title |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mls27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\">{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=October 26, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #25 Blonde Bombshell |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/27/top-50-mls-cup-moments-25-blonde-bombshell |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. took a 1\u20130 lead in the 37th minute after a cross from Sanneh to Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce, who [[dummy (football)|dummied]] the ball at the top of the penalty area. The cross fell to Moreno, who took a short shot from {{convert|12|yd|m}} that rolled past [[Marcus Hahnemann]] and two Colorado defenders.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\"/> The Rapids were outshot 8\u20135 in the first half, with only one shot in the final 24 minutes.<ref name=\"Rocky\">{{cite news |last=Lindsay |first=John |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United way isn't generous to Rapids |page=C4 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> They attempted to find an equalizer early in the second half and had two chances through [[David Pati\u00f1o]] that were not finished after missing a through ball and later hitting teammate [[Steve Rammel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Gary |date=October 26, 1997 |title=D.C. United, again |page=S12 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=\"SS-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=October 22, 1997 |title=United they stand |pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ C9], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894996/united-they-stand-p-c14/ C14] |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nSanneh extended the lead for D.C. in the 68th minute, scoring with a header at the far post on a high cross from [[John Harkes]] after cleaning up a cleared corner kick. The team continued its attacking pressure, but shifted to a defensive style to prepare for counterattacks from the Rapids.<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Marcelo Balboa moved up into the midfield and attempted a [[bicycle kick]] in the 70th minute that was saved by Garlick.<ref>{{cite news |last=Firchau |first=Nick |date=October 23, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #28 Biker Boss |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/24/top-50-mls-cup-moments-28-biker-boss |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Colorado earned a consolation goal in the 75th minute from substitute [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]], who struck the ball from a tight angle in the penalty area on an assist from Pati\u00f1o.<ref name=\"SS-Recap\"/> A chance to equalize came less than a minute later as Rapids forward [[Wolde Harris]] took an unimpeded shot from {{convert|20|yd|m}} that flew over the crossbar.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"NYT-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United Takes Lead, Then Holds On to Retain Its Title |page=C3 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/27/sports/soccer-united-takes-lead-then-holds-on-to-retain-its-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> D.C. responded with their own attacks that were shut down by the Rapids with uncalled fouls that were described as potential [[penalty kick]]s.<ref name=\"Globe-Recap\"/> The hosts won 2\u20131 to claim their second MLS Cup title;<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Moreno was named the MLS Cup [[most valuable player]] for his performance, which included setting up plays throughout the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tucker |first=Bryan |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Moreno Makes Most of Opportunity |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/bryan27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news |last=Jensen |first=Mike |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United again reigns in the rain |page=D3 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394764/dc_united_again_reigns_in_the_rain/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date = October 26, 1997\n|time = 3:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[D.C. United]]\n|score = 2\u20131\n|report= [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/1997 Report]\n|team2 = [[Colorado Rapids]]\n|goals1 = \n*[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Moreno]] {{goal|37}}\n*[[Tony Sanneh|Sanneh]] {{goal|68}}\n|goals2 = [[Adri\u00e1n Paz|Paz]] {{goal|75}}\n|stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]]\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|attendance = 57,431\n|referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:92%;\"\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _thinredborder\n |pattern_b  = _DCU_96h\n |pattern_ra = _thinredborder\n |pattern_sh = _DCU_96\n |pattern_so = _3_stripes_white\n |leftarm    = 000000\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = 000000\n |shorts     = 000000\n |socks      = 000000\n |title      = D.C. United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = \n |pattern_b  = \n |pattern_ra = \n |pattern_sh = \n |pattern_so = \n |leftarm    = FFFFFF\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = FFFFFF\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = FFFFFF\n |title      = Colorado Rapids\n}}\n|}\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n!width=25| !!wi