} [[Coldplay]]\n| Musicians\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Lionel Messi]]\n| Athlete ([[Association football]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Ed Sheeran]]\n| Musician\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| {{flagicon|POR}} [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]\n| Athlete ([[Association football]])\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ 2019 <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/celebrities/#48ff68dd5947|title= The Celebrity 100: The World's Highest-Paid Entertainers of 2019|date=10 July 2019|work= [[Forbes]]|}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | No.\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipient\n! scope=\"col\" | Career\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Taylor Swift]]\n| [[Musician]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Kylie Jenner]]\n| [[Businessperson]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Kanye West]]\n| [[Rapper]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Lionel Messi]]\n| [[Athlete]] ([[Association football]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Ed Sheeran]]\n| Musician\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| {{flagicon|PRT}} [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]\n|  [[Athlete]] ([[Association football]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Neymar]]\n|  [[Athlete]] ([[Association football]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[The Eagles]]\n| [[Music group]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Phil McGraw]]\n| [[Psychologist]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Canelo Alvarez|Saul \"Canelo\" Alvarez]]\n| Athlete ([[Boxer]])\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.forbes.com/wealth/celebrities/list The Celebrity 100, latest]\n\n{{Forbes Magazine Lists}}\n\n[[Category:Annual magazine issues]]\n[[Category:Lists of celebrities]]\n[[Category:Forbes lists]]\n", "name_user": "Carolineistooswagfrou", "label": "safe", "comment": "I had to update the people, they have changed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forbes_Celebrity_100"}
{"title_page": "Rodney Sturdee", "text_new": "[[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)| Rear Admiral]] '''Arthur Rodney Barry Sturdee''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSO]] (6 December 1919 \u2013 6 October 2009) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who saw active service in the Second World War on HMS ''Exeter'' and in minesweepers and ended his career as Flag Officer, Gibraltar.\n==Early life==\nThe son of a naval officer, Commander Barry Victor Sturdee,<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rear-admiral-rodney-sturdee-flag-officer-gibraltar-1969-72-5660ml2p6h8 Rear Admiral Rodney Sturdee: Flag Officer Gibraltar 1969 72] (obituary) in [[The Times]], 5 November 2009, accessed 17 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> whose father had been a Church of England clergyman in Devon and a first cousin of [[Admiral of the Fleet]] [[Doveton Sturdee|Sir Doveton Sturdee]],<ref> [http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Barry_Victor_Sturdee Barry Victor Sturdee] at dreadnoughtproject.org, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> the young Sturdee was educated at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], passing out on 1 September 1938, at the age of eighteen, and joining the Royal Navy as a [[midshipman]].<ref>The Navy List 1938, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CXcTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false  p. 230</ref> \n==Career==\n[[File:HMS Exeter (68) off Coco Solo c1939.jpg|thumb|HMS Exeter]] When Britain and France declared war on Germany in 1939, Sturdee was serving in the South Atlantic on the [[York-class cruiser]] [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']], which had been sent to help the survivors of an earthquake in [[Chile]]. His ship was conveniently placed to be sent to take part in the [[Battle of the River Plate]] of December 1939 and was badly damaged by enemy fire.<ref name=times/> She then steamed for the [[Falkland Islands]], where she stayed for several weeks to make repairs.<ref>M. J. Whitley, ''Cruisers of World War Two An International Encyclopedia'' (London: Cassell, 1995), p. 95</ref> On 29 February 1940, with [[F. S. Bell|Captain F. S. Bell]] and other officers and men of ''Exeter'', Sturdee was given the [[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], when they marched through the streets with the ship\u2019s shell-torn [[White Ensign]], welcomed by a crowd of 50,000.<ref name=cornforth>David Cornforth, [http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/EM/otherexeters.html Royal Navy Ships Named HMS Exeter] (2005) at Exeter Memories, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625021302/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/otherexeters.html archived here]</ref>\n[[File:HMS Algerine FL472.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Algerine'']]\nSturdee was promoted to Sub-Lieutenant in January 1941, and Lieutenant a month later.<ref name=unithistories> [https://www.unithistories.com/officers/RN_officersS3.html STURDEE Arthur Rodney Barry\u201d] at unithistories.com, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> He was transferred to service in the [[Algerine-class minesweeper|''Algerine''-class]] [[minesweeper]]s [[HMS Fly|HMS ''Fly'']], ''St Kilda, Albacore, Squall, Waterwitch, Cadmus, Nimbus, Stornoway, Acute'' and ''Brave'',<ref> [http://www.mcdoa.org.uk/ww_ii_awards_for_rn_minesweeping_S.htm WW II Awards for RN Minesweeping - MCDOA] at mcdoa.org.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> and on 12 June 1945 was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his work in arduous minesweeping operations on the coasts of Italy. The citation read \u201cfor skill, perseverance and great devotion to duty\u201d.<ref name=times/> From July to September 1945, he was posted to an onshore navigation course, and then in September rejoined HMS ''Fly'' as Navigating Officer.<ref name=unithistories/>\n\nSturdee was promoted to Lieutenant-Commander in February 1949, Commander in December 1952, Captain in June 1960, and Rear Admiral on 7 July 1969,<ref name=unithistories/> ending his naval career as [[British Forces Gibraltar#Administration|Flag Officer]], [[Gibraltar]], from October 1969 to January 1972,<ref name=times/> with the further title of Admiral Superintendant, [[Gibdock|HM Dockyard, Gibraltar]].<ref>[[Jane's Fighting Ships]] (Sampson Low, Marston and Company, 1969), p. 304</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 1972, Sturdee retired from the navy to his native [[Worcestershire]]<ref name=times/> and soon took up a new job as bursar at [[Malvern Girls College]], which lasted until 1985. He was president of the Worcestershire branch of the [[Royal British Legion]] and also of the Malvern Sea Cadets.<ref name=gazette>[https://www.malverngazette.co.uk/news/malvern/4702437.navy-man-enjoyed-distinguished-career/ \u201cNavy man enjoyed distinguished career\u201d] in ''[[Malvern Gazette]]'', 26 October 2009</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1953, Sturdee married firstly in [[Mulhouse]], [[Alsace]], Marie-Claire Amstoutz, whom he met while she was working at the [[Embassy of France, London|French Embassy in London]]. They had a son and a daughter, Dominique and Christopher. His first wife died in 1995, and in 2001, at the age of 81, Sturdee married secondly, a widow with a daughter, and they lived together at Castlemorton Common in the [[Malvern Hills]] until his death.<ref name=gazette/>\n\n==Honours==\n*Concepcion Award (Chile), 24 January 1939<ref name=unithistories/>\n*[[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], 29 February 1940<ref name=cornforth/>\n*Distinguished Service Cross, 1945<ref name=times/>\n*[[Companion of the Order of the Bath]], June 1971<ref>Supplement to [[The London Gazette]], 12 June 1971, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45384/supplement/5958/data.pdf p. 5958]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sturdee, Arthur Rodney Barry}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "[[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)| Rear Admiral]] '''Arthur Rodney Barry Sturdee''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSO]] (6 December 1919 \u2013 6 October 2009) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who saw active service in the Second World War on HMS ''Exeter'' and in minesweepers and ended his career as Flag Officer, Gibraltar.\n==Life==\nThe son of a naval officer, Commander Barry Victor Sturdee,<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rear-admiral-rodney-sturdee-flag-officer-gibraltar-1969-72-5660ml2p6h8 Rear Admiral Rodney Sturdee: Flag Officer Gibraltar 1969 72] (obituary) in [[The Times]], 5 November 2009, accessed 17 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> whose father had been a Church of England clergyman in Devon and a first cousin of [[Admiral of the Fleet]] [[Doveton Sturdee|Sir Doveton Sturdee]],<ref> [http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Barry_Victor_Sturdee Barry Victor Sturdee] at dreadnoughtproject.org, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> the young Sturdee was educated at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], passing out on 1 September 1938, at the age of eighteen, and joining the Royal Navy as a [[midshipman]].<ref>The Navy List 1938, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CXcTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false  p. 230</ref> [[File:HMS Exeter (68) off Coco Solo c1939.jpg|thumb|HMS Exeter]] When war with Germany broke out the next year, Sturdee was serving in the South Atlantic on the [[York-class cruiser]] [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']], which had been sent to help the survivors of an earthquake in [[Chile]]. His ship was conveniently placed to be sent to take part in the [[Battle of the River Plate]] of December 1939 and was badly damaged by enemy fire.<ref name=times/> She then steamed for the [[Falkland Islands]], where she stayed for several weeks to make repairs.<ref>M. J. Whitley, ''Cruisers of World War Two An International Encyclopedia'' (London: Cassell, 1995), p. 95</ref> On 29 February 1940, with [[F. S. Bell|Captain F. S. Bell]] and other officers and men of ''Exeter'', Sturdee was given the [[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], when they marched through the streets with the ship\u2019s shell-torn [[White Ensign]], welcomed by a crowd of 50,000.<ref name=cornforth>David Cornforth, [http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/EM/otherexeters.html Royal Navy Ships Named HMS Exeter] (2005) at Exeter Memories, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625021302/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/otherexeters.html archived here]</ref>\n[[File:HMS Algerine FL472.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Algerine'']]\nSturdee was promoted to Sub-Lieutenant in January 1941, and Lieutenant a month later.<ref name=unithistories> [https://www.unithistories.com/officers/RN_officersS3.html STURDEE Arthur Rodney Barry\u201d] at unithistories.com, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> He was transferred to service in the [[Algerine-class minesweeper|''Algerine''-class]] [[minesweeper]]s [[HMS Fly|HMS ''Fly'']], ''St Kilda, Albacore, Squall, Waterwitch, Cadmus, Nimbus, Stornoway, Acute'' and ''Brave'',<ref> [http://www.mcdoa.org.uk/ww_ii_awards_for_rn_minesweeping_S.htm WW II Awards for RN Minesweeping - MCDOA] at mcdoa.org.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> and on 12 June 1945 was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his work in arduous minesweeping operations on the coasts of Italy. The citation read \u201cfor skill, perseverance and great devotion to duty\u201d.<ref name=times/> From July to September 1945, he was posted to an onshore navigation course, and then in September rejoined HMS ''Fly'' as Navigating Officer.<ref name=unithistories/>\n\nSturdee was promoted to Lieutenant-Commander in February 1949, Commander in December 1952, Captain in June 1960, and Rear Admiral on 7 July 1969,<ref name=unithistories/> ending his naval career as [[British Forces Gibraltar#Administration|Flag Officer]], [[Gibraltar]], from October 1969 to January 1972,<ref name=times/> with the further title of Admiral Superintendant, [[Gibdock|HM Dockyard, Gibraltar]].<ref>[[Jane's Fighting Ships]] (Sampson Low, Marston and Company, 1969), p. 304</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 1972, Sturdee retired from the navy to his native [[Worcestershire]]<ref name=times/> and soon took up a new job as bursar at [[Malvern Girls College]], which lasted until 1985. He was president of the Worcestershire branch of the [[Royal British Legion]] and also of the Malvern Sea Cadets.<ref name=gazette>[https://www.malverngazette.co.uk/news/malvern/4702437.navy-man-enjoyed-distinguished-career/ \u201cNavy man enjoyed distinguished career\u201d] in ''[[Malvern Gazette]]'', 26 October 2009</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1953, Sturdee married firstly in [[Mulhouse]], [[Alsace]], Marie-Claire Amstoutz, whom he met while she was working at the [[Embassy of France, London|French Embassy in London]]. They had a son and a daughter, Dominique and Christopher. His first wife died in 1995, and in 2001, at the age of 81, Sturdee married secondly, a widow with a daughter, and they lived together at Castlemorton Common in the [[Malvern Hills]] until his death.<ref name=gazette/>\n\n==Honours==\n*Concepcion Award (Chile), 24 January 1939<ref name=unithistories/>\n*[[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], 29 February 1940<ref name=cornforth/>\n*Distinguished Service Cross, 1945<ref name=times/>\n*[[Companion of the Order of the Bath]], June 1971<ref>Supplement to [[The London Gazette]], 12 June 1971, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45384/supplement/5958/data.pdf p. 5958]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sturdee, Arthur Rodney Barry}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n", "